{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529974"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:00:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:00:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14479"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14479"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.05,0.03,0.65,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55726"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7174"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41270"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4925"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11061"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12451"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43531"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55726"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for pre-pregnancy counselling. She had pre-eclampsia during her first pregnancy two years ago, which resulted in an emergency caesarean section at 34 weeks gestation. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is planning to conceive again in the next few months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 27 kg/m2. Urinalysis shows no proteinuria, and her blood pressure is 118/76 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate recommendation for her next pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start low-dose aspirin at 20 weeks gestation","Begin calcium supplementation immediately","Commence low-molecular-weight heparin when pregnancy is confirmed","Start low-dose aspirin before 16 weeks gestation","Initiate antihypertensive medication when pregnancy is confirmed"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor this patient with a history of pre-eclampsia in her previous pregnancy, the most appropriate recommendation for her next pregnancy is to \u003Cstrong\u003Estart low-dose aspirin before 16 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E. Women with a history of pre-eclampsia are considered high-risk for recurrence in subsequent pregnancies. Low-dose aspirin (75-150 mg daily) has been shown to reduce the risk of pre-eclampsia, particularly when started early in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting low-dose aspirin at 20 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E is too late to achieve maximum benefit. The current recommendation is to start aspirin before 16 weeks of gestation, ideally between 12-16 weeks, for optimal prevention of pre-eclampsia in high-risk women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeginning calcium supplementation immediately\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended for all women with a history of pre-eclampsia. While calcium supplementation may be beneficial in populations with low dietary calcium intake, it is not the first-line preventive strategy for pre-eclampsia in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing low-molecular-weight heparin when pregnancy is confirmed\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended for pre-eclampsia prevention. Heparin may be considered in women with certain thrombophilias or recurrent pregnancy loss, but it is not indicated based solely on a history of pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating antihypertensive medication when pregnancy is confirmed\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for this patient. She currently has normal blood pressure and no evidence of chronic hypertension. Antihypertensive medications are used to treat hypertension in pregnancy but are not used prophylactically to prevent pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to recommending low-dose aspirin, pre-pregnancy counselling for this patient should include advice on maintaining a healthy lifestyle, achieving a normal BMI, and ensuring good control of any other medical conditions. Regular antenatal care and monitoring will be crucial in her next pregnancy due to her increased risk of recurrent pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Women with a history of pre-eclampsia are at increased risk of recurrence in subsequent pregnancies.","Low-dose aspirin (75-150 mg daily) is recommended for pre-eclampsia prevention in high-risk women, starting before 16 weeks of gestation.","Pre-pregnancy counselling is important for women with a history of pre-eclampsia to optimize health and discuss preventive strategies for future pregnancies."],"references":["Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand. Hypertension in pregnancy guideline 2023. SOMANZ; 2023. Available from: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2023/06/SOMANZ_Hypertension_in_Pregnancy_Guideline_2023_Updated_30.6.23.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41270"}},"question":{"data